context: <a1_0><b9_0>Between 1847 and 1850<b9_0/><a1_0/>, when Blore was building <a5_0>the new east wing<a5_0/>, the <a0_0><b8_0>Brighton Pavilion<b8_0/><a0_0/> was once again plundered of its fittings. As a result, many of the rooms in the new wing have a distinctly <a2_0><a6_0><b10_0><b12_0>oriental<b12_0/><b10_0/><a6_0/><a2_0/> atmosphere. <a7_0>The red and blue Chinese Luncheon Room<a7_0/> is made up from parts of the Brighton Banqueting and Music Rooms with a <a3_0>large oriental chimney piece<a3_0/> sculpted by Richard Westmacott. The Yellow Drawing Room has wallpaper supplied in 1817 for the Brighton Saloon, and a chimney piece which is a European vision of how the Chinese chimney piece may appear. It has nodding mandarins in niches and fearsome winged dragons, designed by <a4_0><b11_0>Robert Jones<b11_0/><a4_0/>.
